</taxonomicName>
is assessed as Data Deficient (DD) at this time (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC383F3191A155543CEF5E2A71DFA0B" author="IUCN" box="[649,774,1468,1490]" journalOrPublisher="IUNC, Gland, Switzerland, and Cambridge, United Kingdom" pageId="10" pageNumber="190" refId="ref21499" refString="IUCN. 2001. IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria, 3.1. Prepared by the IUCN Species Survival Commission. IUNC, Gland, Switzerland, and Cambridge, United Kingdom." title="IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria, 3.1. Prepared by the IUCN Species Survival Commission" type="book" year="2001">IUCN, 2001</bibRefCitation>
). This species is apparently rare and only known from a few collections, the type and three others. Further, because of habitat destruction, this species may at least be Vulnerable (VU), perhaps Endangered (EN).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C348AD89191A155443DCF637A564FC73" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="191" pageId="10" pageNumber="190" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BEDFE02191A155443DCF637A4C7FD9B" blockId="10.[643,1153,1640,1811]" lastBlockId="11.[143,654,196,939]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="191" pageId="10" pageNumber="190">
<emphasis id="B9262210191A155543DCF637A6E6F9A7" box="[667,765,1641,1662]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="190">Discussion</emphasis>
. We have only examined three specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C528581191A1555439BF6D8A7A8F945" authorityName="Seigler &amp; Ebinger &amp; Riggins &amp; Terra &amp; Miller" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Seigler &amp; Ebinger &amp; Riggins &amp; Terra &amp; Miller" baseAuthorityYear="2017" box="[732,947,1670,1692]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Parasenegalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="10" pageNumber="190" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="santosii">
<emphasis id="B9262210191A1555439BF6D8A7A8F945" box="[732,947,1670,1692]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="190">Parasenegalia santosii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a photograph, and a drawing of the type of this taxon. Two specimens from Bahia were seen by V. Terra. One additional collection has been reported to represent this species by Barros and Morim (2014) from Brazil (Espírito Santo, Aracruz, ES–445, Km. 10, fazenda Limoeiro, 19 
<emphasis id="B9262210191B155441EFF0BCA4ABFF21" bold="true" box="[168,176,226,248]" pageId="11" pageNumber="191">°</emphasis>
40 
<emphasis id="B9262210191B1554418DF0BCA4C9FF21" bold="true" box="[202,210,226,248]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="191">'</emphasis>
36 
<emphasis id="B9262210191B155441ACF0BCA4E8FF21" bold="true" box="[235,243,226,248]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="191">''</emphasis>
S, 40 
<emphasis id="B9262210191B15544069F0BCA52DFF21" bold="true" box="[302,310,226,248]" pageId="11" pageNumber="191">°</emphasis>
0 9 
<emphasis id="B9262210191B15544017F0BCA543FF21" bold="true" box="[336,344,226,248]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="191">'</emphasis>
0 
<emphasis id="B9262210191B15544022F0BCA576FF21" bold="true" box="[357,365,226,248]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="191">''</emphasis>
W, 4 Dec. 2014. 
<emphasis id="B9262210191B1554436CF0BDA575FECF" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="191">H. Cavalcante de Lima 7 92 1</emphasis>
(RB RB6 1 2 2 4 0 [barcode] RB00905083). We have only seen an image of this collection. This specimen differs in several characters from the original description for 
<taxonomicName id="4C528581191B1554408AF105A62AFEA9" authorityName="Seigler &amp; Ebinger &amp; Riggins &amp; Terra &amp; Miller" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Seigler &amp; Ebinger &amp; Riggins &amp; Terra &amp; Miller" baseAuthorityYear="2017" box="[461,561,347,368]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Parasenegalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="11" pageNumber="191" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="santosii">
<emphasis id="B9262210191B1554408AF105A62AFEA9" box="[461,561,347,368]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="191">P. santosii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, e.g., the number of leaflets/pinna (17 to 20) and the position of the petiolar gland (on the petiole below the lowermost pair of pinnae). It seems probable that this species is more widespread than previously thought. In any case, additional collections are required to establish the range of character variation and occurrence of the species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEDFE02191B155441E0F215A564FC73" blockId="11.[143,654,196,939]" pageId="11" pageNumber="191">
Lewis (1 9 9 6) suggested that 
<taxonomicName id="4C528581191B155440BAF215A4C3FDA7" authorityName="Seigler &amp; Ebinger &amp; Riggins &amp; Terra &amp; Miller" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Seigler &amp; Ebinger &amp; Riggins &amp; Terra &amp; Miller" baseAuthorityYear="2017" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Parasenegalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="11" pageNumber="191" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="santosii">
<emphasis id="B9262210191B155440BAF215A4C3FDA7" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="191">Parasenegalia santosii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(discussed as 
<taxonomicName id="4C528581191B15544039F237A60DFDA7" box="[382,534,617,639]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acacia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="11" pageNumber="191" phylum="Magnoliopsida" rank="species" species="santosii">
<emphasis id="B9262210191B15544039F237A60DFDA7" box="[382,534,617,639]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="191">Acacia santosii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) is closely related to 
<emphasis id="B9262210191B15544041F2D8A599FD45" box="[262,386,646,668]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="191">A. ambigua</emphasis>
Vogel (
<emphasis id="B9262210191B155440A4F2D8A5ECFD45" bold="true" box="[483,503,646,668]" pageId="11" pageNumber="191">≡</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C528581191B1554434FF2D9A54AFD62" authority="Seigler &amp; Ebinger" authorityName="Seigler &amp; Ebinger &amp; Riggins &amp; Terra &amp; Miller" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Seigler &amp; Ebinger &amp; Riggins &amp; Terra &amp; Miller" baseAuthorityYear="2017" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Parasenegalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="11" pageNumber="191" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="vogeliana">
<emphasis id="B9262210191B1554434FF2D9A696FD45" box="[520,653,646,668]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="191">P. vogeliana</emphasis>
Seigler &amp; Ebinger
</taxonomicName>
), a species from Hispaniola. 
<taxonomicName id="4C528581191B155441C8F29CA56EFD01" authorityName="Seigler &amp; Ebinger &amp; Riggins &amp; Terra &amp; Miller" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Seigler &amp; Ebinger &amp; Riggins &amp; Terra &amp; Miller" baseAuthorityYear="2017" box="[143,373,706,728]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Parasenegalia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="11" pageNumber="191" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="santosii">
<emphasis id="B9262210191B155441C8F29CA56EFD01" box="[143,373,706,728]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="191">Parasenegalia santosii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is easily separated from other members of the genus with globose inflorescences by the elongated receptacle. This species also has a columnar petiolar gland, while other members of the genus have sessile petiolar glands. Although anther glands are reported as lacking (Lewis, 1 9 9 6), they are present on specimen 
<emphasis id="B9262210191B15544333F329A55AFC73" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="191">M. Magalhães 19 4 9 2</emphasis>
(NY).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
